title.narrative: BUILDING STAFF CAPACITIES TO DELIVER QUALITY NUTRITION SERVICES

description.narrative: By 2022, actors in nutrition- specific and -sensitive sectors have capacity to deliver quality nutrition services., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Supply And Logistics, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, adolescent girls, women of childbearing age (especially pregnant and breastfeeding women) and their children aged 0-59 months adopt better nutrition practices and use quality nutrition-specific and sensitive services.

description.narrative: UNICEF provided technical and therapeutic products for treatment of 110,780 severe acute malnourished (SAM) children from January to November 2021 nationwide (73 per cent), with cure, death, and default rates of 91.9 per cent, 1.9 ;per cent, and 6.2 per cent, respectively, above the minimum standards. 3,322,605 children aged 6-59 years (97.7 per cent) received vitamin A supplementation and screening for acute malnutrition, and those aged 12-59 years were dewormed with COVID-19 prevention measures incorporated. The implementation of small-scale maternal nutrition program with multiple micronutrient to pregnant women started in the demonstration area in August 2021. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:28/01/2022
